Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

## Approach 1: Pass product ID as a query parameter

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

## Approach 2: Pass the full object via navigation parameters

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
}
```

## Receiving data with IQueryAttributable

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from service
            LoadProduct(ProductId);
        }

        // Approach 2: full object passed via dictionary
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
            ProductId = product.Id;
        }
    }

    private async void LoadProduct(string id)
    {
        Product = await _productService.GetByIdAsync(id);
    }
}
```

## Route registration & page wiring

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs or AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));

// DI registration
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>();
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsViewModel>();
```

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | Query string | Dictionary parameter |
|---|---|---|
| Data type | string only | any object |
| Survives deep link / URI | ✅ | ❌ |
| No serialization needed | ❌ | ✅ |

Use query strings for simple IDs (and when deep-link support matters). Use the dictionary overload when you already have the object in memory and want to avoid a redundant fetch.
